<DOC><DOCNO> AP880512-0270 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 0702EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   05-12 0508</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0529</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Major banks have raised their prime lendingrates for the first time since the October stock market crash,heralding a period of more expensive loans for purchases rangingfrom plant machinery to homes and cars.   The banks, pressured by increased costs of borrowing moneythemselves, raised their prime lending rates Wednesday to 9 percentfrom 8.5 percent, nearly erasing the results of three ratedecreases over the past seven months. Chase Manhattan Bank led themove and was followed by competitors.   The prime rate is used to calculate business and consumer loans.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Local union members narrowly have ratified aUnited Auto Workers contract covering 66,000 Chrysler Corp.workers, according to union officials.   The contract was approved nationally Wednesday by about 54percent of those voting at local union halls in 15 states, saidunion officials who spoke on condition they not be identified.   Union officials said the narrow margin apparently stemmed partlyfrom rank-and-file displeasure over a number of factors surroundingthe contract, which established job-protecting provisions similarto those in effect at General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   USG Corp. has claimed victory in a proxy battle,saying shareholders had voted for a management-backed directorsslate over one supporting an investor group's $2.2 billion hostiletakeover bid.   The vote for six seats on the 15-member board of the buildingmaterials company could prove a turning point in the nearly8-month-old battle for control of USG being waged by DesertPartners L.P. of Midland, Texas.   Robert J. Day, USG's chairman and chief executive, said proxiesreceived before the close of balloting at Wednesday's annualshareholders meeting indicated the management-backed slate wouldget more than 50 percent of the votes. The official ballot resultswill be announced May 20.</TEXT><DATELINE>ROLLING MEADOWS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Staley Continental Inc. has metwith British sugar refiner Tate andamp; Lyle PLC, which announced aone-day extension of its $1.38 billion buyout bid for Staley.   But Staley, a major U.S. producer of corn syrup and food-servicesupplies, said Wednesday the talks with its English suitor did notmean it was ready to sell out. Staley spokesman David Satterfieldsaid his company was continuing negotiations with other parties aswell.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Consumers' confidence rebounded in April,suggesting consumer spending will remain strong in coming months, aprivate study said.   The report Wednesday by the Conference Board, a businessresearch organization, indicated its index of consumer confidencerose to 114.6 in April from 112.7 in March, leaving it just belowits level of 114.9 in February.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Federal Reserve Board has issued rulesrequiring banks, savings institutions and credit unions to meetstrict deadlines in making funds from check deposits available tocustomers.   The new rules, effective Sept. 1, require financial institutionsto give customers access to deposited funds within one, three orseven days, depending on the type of check deposited. The ruleswere issued Wednesday.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>